---
import ContentPageHero from './ContentPageHero.astro';
---

<div class="essay-page manifesto-page">
    <ContentPageHero
        eyebrow="Foundations / Inspiration"
        title="Stay hungry. Stay foolish."
    />

    <section class="page-module manifesto-prose manifesto-prose--intro">
        <p>
            I wasn't alive when the <a
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whole_Earth_Catalog?utm_source=galexc"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noreferrer">Whole Earth Catalog</a
            > was in print and I honestly had no idea what it was until a few years
            ago. For whatever reason, I am struck by its <a
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whole_Earth_Catalog#/media/File:WEC-69F-C.jpg"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noreferrer">ethos</a
            > (as I understand it) and I often remind myself to try staying hungry
            and foolish. In today's technical landscape, however, this can easily
            push you towards endless acceleration — so I try to hold this against
            the <a
                href="https://longnow.org?utm_source=galexc"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noreferrer">Long Now's</a
            > much longer view, and ask whether what I'm building will still matter
            in decades, not just this week. I'm not entirely what what will.
        </p>

        <figure
            class="manifesto-inline-artifact manifesto-inline-artifact--intro mx-auto my-[1.8rem] xs:mx-[1.8rem]"
        >
            <button
                class="manifesto-inline-artifact__trigger"
                type="button"
                data-manifesto-lightbox-open
                aria-label="Expand Whole Earth Epilog image"
            >
                <img
                    src="/stay-hungry-stay-foolish.png"
                    alt="Stay hungry. Stay foolish. image from Gilman's framed Whole Earth Epilog"
                />
            </button>
            <figcaption>
                Exhibit 01 - An original copy of the Whole Earth Epilog in my
                office, which provides a meaningful reminder for me.
            </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <dialog class="manifesto-lightbox" data-manifesto-lightbox>
            <button
                class="manifesto-lightbox__close"
                type="button"
                data-manifesto-lightbox-close
                aria-label="Close expanded image"
            >
                ×
            </button>
            <img
                class="manifesto-lightbox__image"
                src="/stay-hungry-stay-foolish.png"
                alt="Stay hungry. Stay foolish. image from Gilman's framed Whole Earth Epilog"
            />
        </dialog>

        <script is:inline>
            (() => {
                const dialog = document.querySelector(
                    '[data-manifesto-lightbox]',
                );
                const openButton = document.querySelector(
                    '[data-manifesto-lightbox-open]',
                );
                const closeButton = document.querySelector(
                    '[data-manifesto-lightbox-close]',
                );

                if (!(dialog instanceof HTMLDialogElement)) return;

                openButton?.addEventListener('click', () => dialog.showModal());
                closeButton?.addEventListener('click', () => dialog.close());
                dialog.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
                    const rect = dialog.getBoundingClientRect();
                    const inside =
                        rect.top <= event.clientY &&
                        event.clientY <= rect.top + rect.height &&
                        rect.left <= event.clientX &&
                        event.clientX <= rect.left + rect.width;
                    if (!inside) dialog.close();
                });
            })();
        </script>

        <p>
            I've seen several incredible innovations in the last ~15 years of
            deploying machine learning into professional-grade products
            (Tensorflow, anyone? Serverless compute?). That said, LLMs have
            unlocked a step-change in capabilities unlike anything I've
            personally experienced. As one should, I turn to my nerd friends,
            mentors, colleagues and communities like <a
                href="https://agentcribs.com/"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noreferrer">Agent Cribs</a
            > to try navigating this wacky, ever-changing world.
        </p>

        <p>
            A few months ago I had an incredible experience that changed the
            trajectory of my AI-journey. My friend, Kyle, had his AI, KyleOps,
            share an overview of what they had been building. The level of
            clarity and depth across a complex, evolving system was unlike
            anything I had ever seen before. Trying to explain complex DevOps
            concepts and setups is seriously challenging in the best of
            times...KyleOps cranked it out in a few minutes with an extremely
            cogent, actionable, helpful summary. It was truly inspiring. The
            moment I saw that, I felt compelled to just start building.
        </p>

        <section>
            <blockquote
                class="manifesto-quote manifesto-quote-strong manifesto-quote--wide"
            >
                <p>
                    I hope you can use GalexC as the spark to build <em>your</em
                    >
                    personal AI.
                </p>
            </blockquote>
        </section>
    </section>
</div>
